@section mdr_hw_block Block Diagram Position

`hello_world` has no message bus dependencies and no downstream consumers.
It can be loaded alongside any set of models without affecting their signal
state. In a real simulation block diagram it would be omitted entirely — its
place is in the test harness, not the signal chain.

@verbatim
  [Scheduler]
       |
       v
 +-------------+
 | hello_world |   (no inputs, no outputs)
 +-------------+
@endverbatim

@section mdr_hw_verification Verification

Run the scenario from the `python/` directory:

@code{.sh}
python3 scenarios/hello_world.py
@endcode

Expected console output (5-second run at 1 Hz):

@code{.sh}
Hello World!
sim_time = 0.000000 s
sim_time = 1.000000 s
sim_time = 2.000000 s
sim_time = 3.000000 s
sim_time = 4.000000 s
So Long, and Thanks for All the Fish!
@endcode

| Check | Expected | Status |
|---|---|---|
| `model_initialize` fires once | "Hello World!" printed exactly once | PASS |
| `model_update` fires at 1 Hz | 5 lines for a 5 s run | PASS |
| Sim time increments by 1.0 s | Lines show 0, 1, 2, 3, 4 | PASS |
| `model_finalize` fires once | Closing message printed after loop | PASS |
| No message bus side effects | No signals present on bus after run | PASS |
